 This not only confirms that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already widely accepted, but also provides details that fossils generally cannot provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
 Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown on the upper side and light or carotenoid-colored on the underside.
 The find also provides insights into the evolution of feathers in birds.
 Because dinosaur feathers lack a well-developed shaft, called the rachis, but do have other features of feathers — barbs and barbules — the researchers concluded that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development than these other features.
 The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flying, but rather for temperature regulation or for showing off. The researchers suspected that the sample, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, shows the plumage of an adult and not the down of a chick.
 The researchers claimed that, although this is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows the plumage of an adult and not downy feathers.
