 All the cave entrances, including the "Seven Sisters", have a diameter of at least 100 to 250 meters (328 to 820 feet).
 Infrared images show temperature differences between night and day, which indicate that these are probably caves.
 "They are colder than the surrounding surface during the day and warmer at night."
 "Their thermal behavior is not as uniform as that of large caves on Earth, which often have a fairly constant temperature, but it does match what you would expect from deep holes in the ground," said Glen Cushing of the Astrogeology Team of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff, Arizona.
 In France, voting is traditionally a low-tech experience: Voters isolate themselves in a booth and slip a pre-printed sheet of paper, on which the candidate of their choice is written, into an envelope.
 After the officials have confirmed the identity of the voter, the voter drops the envelope into the ballot box and signs the voter list.
 French election law sets the timetable quite strictly.
 Since 1988, ballot boxes have had to be transparent so that voters and observers can verify that no ballots are present at the start of the election and that no ballots are added except those of properly counted and authorized voters.
 The candidates can send representatives who will witness every part of the process. At the end of the day, the votes are counted by volunteers under strict supervision and special procedures.
