 Among them are medium-sized cats that eat medium-sized prey, from rabbits to antelopes and deer.
 Finally, there are many small cats (including free-roaming house cats) that eat much smaller prey such as insects, rodents, lizards, and birds.
 The secret of their success is the concept of the niche, a special task that each cat has and which ensures that it does not compete with others.
 Lions are the most social of cats. They live in large groups called prides.
 The packs consist of one to three related adult males, as well as up to thirty females and young.
 Women usually have a close relationship with each other when they live in a large family with sisters and daughters.
 Lion prides behave similarly to wolf or dog prides, animals that are surprisingly similar in behavior to lions (but not other big cats) and are just as deadly to their prey.
 As a versatile athlete, the tiger can climb (albeit not very well), swim, jump great distances, and pull with the force of five times a strong man.
 The tiger is in the same group (genus Panthera) as lions, leopards and jaguars, the only four cats that can roar.
 The roar of the tiger does not sound like the boastful roar of the lion, but rather like a sentence of grumbling roared words.
 Ocelots eat small animals. When they can, they prey on monkeys, snakes, rodents, and birds. Almost all the animals the ocelot hunts are much smaller than it is.
 Scientists think that ocelots use their sense of smell to track and locate prey. They sniff where they have been on the ground.
 They can see very well in the dark with night vision and can move unnoticed. Ocelots hunt their prey by blending in with their surroundings and then pouncing on their prey.
 If a small group of organisms (a small population) is separated from the main population from which it came (for example, if it crosses a mountain range or river, or if it is moved to a new island so that it cannot easily return), they will often find themselves in a different environment than before.
 This new environment has different resources and different competitors, so the new population needs different features or adaptations to be a strong competitor than what it previously needed.
 The original population has not changed at all. It still needs the same adaptations as before.
 Over time, the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, and then it looks less and less like the other population.
 After thousands or even millions of years, two populations may look so different that they can no longer be classified as the same species.
 We call this process speciation, which simply means the creation of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
 Plants generate oxygen that humans breathe, and they take up the carbon dioxide that humans emit (that is, exhale).
 Plants produce their food through photosynthesis with the sun as their source of energy. They also provide shade.
 We build our houses out of plants and make clothes out of plants. We eat mostly plants. Without plants, animals could not survive.
