 The beginning of Taiwan dates back to the 15th century, when European sailors sailed past and documented the name of the island as Ilha Formosa or beautiful island.
 In 1624, the Dutch East India Company established a settlement in southwestern Taiwan, introducing changes in the rice farming methods of the indigenous people and employing Chinese laborers on their rice and sugar plantations.
 In 1683, forces of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1912) took control of Taiwan's western and northern coastal regions and in 1885 declared Taiwan a province of the Qing Empire.
 In 1895, after the defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War (1894–1895), the Qing government signed the Treaty of Shimonoseki, which ceded sovereignty over Taiwan to Japan, which ruled the island until 1945.
