 For example, the most widely used format for still images is 35 mm, which corresponds to the predominant film size at the end of the analogue film era.
 It is still being manufactured today, but more importantly, its image format has been adopted by the image sensor formats of digital cameras.
 In fact, the so-called 35 mm format measures 36 mm in width and 24 mm in height.
 The aspect ratio of this format (divided by twelve, to obtain the simplest integer ratio) is therefore referred to as 3:2.
 Many common formats (the APS format family, for example) have exactly the same or a very similar aspect ratio.
