 Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, from technology push or technological imperative to the strict sense that human fate is determined by an underlying logic that is associated with scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
 Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: first, that the development of technology itself follows a path that is largely beyond cultural or political influence, and second, that technology itself has “effects” on societies that are inherent rather than socially caused.
 One could argue that the automobile has inevitably led to the development of roads.
 However, a nationwide road network for only a small number of cars is not economically viable, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of car ownership.
 The widespread automobile ownership also leads to a higher number of accidents on the roads, which in turn leads to the invention of new techniques in healthcare to repair damaged bodies.
 Romanticism had a strong, culturally deterministic element that drew from writers like Goethe, Fichte, and Schlegel.
 In the context of romanticism, it is geography that shaped individuals. Over time, customs and cultures emerged with reference to this geography and these, since they were in harmony with the place of society, were better than arbitrarily octroiated laws.
 Just as Paris is known as the fashion capital of the world today, Constantinople was the fashion capital of feudal Europe.
 Its fame as a center of luxury began around 400 AD and lasted until about 1100 AD.
 His status declined in the course of the twelfth century, which was mainly due to the fact that the crusaders returned with gifts such as silk and spices, which were considered more valuable than the offer of the Byzantine markets.
 At this time, the title of the world's fashion capital also moved from Constantinople to Paris.
