 Scaffolding is not a learning method, but rather a support that helps individuals in a new learning situation, such as using a new computer program or starting a new project.
 Scaffolding can be both virtual and real. In other words, a teacher is a form of scaffolding, but so is the little clipboard man in Microsoft Office.
 Virtual help is built into the software and should question, suggest and explain work steps that the student alone may not be able to cope with.
