 Research in the twentieth century has shown that there are two pools of genetic variation: hidden and expressed.
 Mutation provides new genetic variation and selection removes these from the pool of expressed variation.
 Segregation and recombination mix the variation between the two pools back and forth with each generation.
 Out in the savannah, it is difficult for a primate with a digestive system like ours to meet its amino acid needs from available plant sources.
 Moreover, it has serious consequences if one fails to do so: growth depression, malnutrition and ultimately death.
 The most readily available plant resources would have been the proteins in leaves and legumes, but these are difficult to digest for primates like us unless they are cooked.
 In contrast, animal food sources (ants, termites, eggs) are not only easily digestible, but also provide large amounts of protein that contains all essential amino acids.
 Overall, it should not surprise us that our own ancestors solved their "protein problem" in a similar way to the way that chimpanzees do in the savannah today.
 Sleep deprivation is the process of deliberately waking up during normal sleep periods and falling asleep again shortly thereafter (10-60 minutes).
 This can be easily achieved by using a relatively quiet alarm clock to alert you without fully waking you up.
 If you are someone who sets the alarm clock in your sleep, you can put it on the other side of the room so that you are forced to get out of bed to turn it off.
 Another biorhythm-based option is to drink a lot of fluid before bed (especially water or tea, which is known for its diuretic effect), so that you are forced to get up to urinate.
