 These plans were however made obsolete almost overnight when over 800,000 soldiers of the Red Army of the Soviet Union poured into the Belarusian and Ukrainian fronts and created them after they had invaded the eastern regions of Poland in violation of the Treaty of Riga, the Soviet-Polish Non-Aggression Pact and other bilateral and multilateral international treaties.
 The use of ships for the transport of goods is by far the most efficient method for transporting large numbers of people and goods across the oceans.
 The Navy's traditional role was to ensure that a nation remains capable of transporting people and goods, while at the same time impeding the enemy's ability to transport people and goods.
 One of the most important recent examples of this is the North Atlantic Campaign in World War II, when the Americans tried to bring manpower and material across the Atlantic to help Britain.
 At the same time, the German Navy tried to stop this traffic mainly with submarines.
 Had the Allies failed, Germany would probably have conquered Britain, as well as the rest of Europe.
 Goats were apparently already domesticated in the Zagros Mountains of Iran about 10,000 years ago.
 Ancient cultures and tribes began to keep them as livestock to easily obtain their milk, fur, meat and hides.
 House goats were usually kept in herds that wandered on hills or other pasture lands.  They were tended by goatherds, much like the more familiar shepherds; often these were children or adolescents. These grazing methods are still used today.
 As early as the 16th century, in England, conveyor belts were built.
 Although the tram tracks consisted only of parallel wooden boards, they allowed the horses that pulled the wagons to reach higher speeds and pull greater loads than on the somewhat rougher roads of the time.
 Very early on, thresholds were introduced to secure the position of the rails. However, it was gradually recognized that rails that carry a band of iron are more efficient.
 This was common, but the iron caused more wear on the wooden wheels of the wagons.
 Finally, wooden wheels were replaced by iron wheels. In 1767, the first completely iron rails were introduced.
 The first known mode of transportation was walking. Man began to walk upright about two million years ago with the emergence of Homo Erectus (which means “upright man”).
 Their predecessors, the Australopithecus, didn’t walk upright so regularly.
 Bipedal species are found in Australopithecus fossils from 4.2 to 3.9 million years ago, although Sahelanthropus may have been bipedal as early as seven million years ago.
