 Traffic flow is the study of the movement of individual drivers and vehicles between two points and the interactions that take place between them.
 Unfortunately, the study of traffic flows is difficult because driver behavior cannot be predicted with one hundred percent certainty.
 Fortunately, drivers tend to behave in a somewhat consistent manner; therefore, traffic flows have a certain consistency and can be roughly represented mathematically.
 To better represent the traffic flow, the relationships between the three most important properties were defined: (1) flow, (2) density and (3) speed.
 These relationships help in the planning, design and operation of facilities on the roadway.
 Insects were the first animals to conquer the skies. Their ability to fly helped them to evade predators and find food and mates more efficiently.
 Most insects can fold their wings back along their bodies.
 This gives them a wider selection of small hiding places in which they can hide from predators.
 Today, dragonflies and mayflies are the only insects that cannot fold their wings back.
 Thousands of years ago, a man named Aristarchus claimed that the sun was at the center of the solar system's movements.
 Some people thought he was right, but many believed the opposite: that the solar system, including the sun (and even the other stars) revolved around the earth.
 This seems reasonable, since it does not seem as if the Earth is moving, does it?
 The Amazon is the second longest and the most water-rich river in the world. It carries more than eight times as much water as the second largest river.
 The Amazon is also the widest river in the world, sometimes up to six miles wide.
 As much as 20 percent of the water that flows into the oceans from the planet's rivers comes from the Amazon.
 The Amazon main stream is 6387 km (3980 miles) long. It takes water from thousands of smaller rivers.
