 The atomic bomb is based on the principle that you need energy to bring together a nucleus with many protons and neutrons.
 It is like rolling a heavy wagon up a hill. When the core is split again, some of this energy is released.
 Some atoms have unstable nuclei, meaning that they will decay at the slightest or no provocation.
 The surface of the Moon is made of rock and dust. The outer layer of the Moon is called the crust.
 The crust is about 70 km thick on the near side and 100 km on the far side.
 It is thinner under the sea and thicker under the highlands.
 On the near side, there could be more Maria because the crust is thinner, making it easier for the lava to rise to the surface.
 Internal theories focus on finding what moves or appeals to people.
 These theories suggest that people have certain needs and/or desires that are internalized over the course of their adulthood.
 These theories deal with what causes certain people to want exactly the things they do, and what influences in their environment cause them to do certain things or not to do certain things.
 Two popular content theories are Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs and Herzberg's Two-Factor Theory.
 In general, two behaviors can emerge when managers begin to manage their former colleagues. One end of the spectrum is the attempt to remain “one of the guys” (or one of the girls).
 This type of manager has trouble making unpopular decisions, enforcing discipline, conducting performance evaluations, assigning responsibilities, and holding employees accountable.
 At the other end of the spectrum, you become a different individual, who has to do everything differently than the team did and take everything for granted.
 Ultimately, the team leader is responsible for the success and failure of the team.
 This behavior often leads to friction between the leaders and the rest of the team.
 Virtual teams are managed to the same high standards as conventional teams, but there are subtle differences.
 Virtual team members often have the function of a contact point for their immediate physical group.
 They often have more autonomy than traditional team members, as their teams can meet in different time zones that may not be considered by the local management.
 The presence of a real "invisible team" (Larson and LaFasto 1989, p. 109) is also a unique component of a virtual team.
 "The ""invisible team"" is the leadership team to which each member reports. The invisible team sets the standards for each member.x"
