 The correlation between brain pathology and behavior supports scientists in their research.
 It has long been known that various types of brain damage such as trauma, injury and tumors affect behavior and cause changes in some brain functions.
 New technologies allow us to see and explore certain brain structures and processes for the first time.
 It provides us with a lot of information and material to build simulation models that help us understand the processes in our head.
 Although strongly associated with science fiction, AI is a major branch of computer science that deals with behavior, learning and intelligent adaptation of machines.
 Research in the field of AI involves the creation of machines to automate tasks that require intelligent behavior.
 Examples include control, the establishment of strategies and timetables, the ability to answer customer diagnoses and questions, as well as handwriting, voice and face recognition.
 Such things have become independent disciplines that focus on finding solutions to real life problems.
 Today, AI systems are widely used in business, medicine, engineering and the military, and have been incorporated into many software applications for home computers and video games.
 Field trips are an important part of any school class. Not infrequently, a teacher would like to take her students to places that are not accessible by bus.
 Virtual excursions are a technical solution. Students can view museum pieces, visit an aquarium or admire beautiful works of art from their classroom.
 Sharing an excursion virtually is also a great way to reflect on a trip and share experiences with future classes.
 For example, students at Bennet School in North Carolina design a web site each year about their trip to the state capital. The web site is redesigned each year, but the previous versions remain online and serve as a scrapbook.
 Blogs can also help improve students' writing skills. While students may have poor grammar and spelling at the beginning of their blogging experience, this usually improves when they have an audience.
 Since students are often a very critical audience, the blogger makes an effort to improve his writing style to avoid criticism.
 Blogging “forces students to learn more about the world around them.” The need to engage the audience inspires students to write intelligently and interestingly (Toto, 2004).
 Blogging is a tool that inspires collaboration and encourages students to continue learning far beyond the traditional school day.
 The appropriate use of blogs "can empower students to become more analytical and critical; by actively responding to Internet materials, students can define their positions in the context of the texts of others and articulate their own perspectives on particular topics" (Oravec, 2002).
