 The Kruger National Park (KNP) is located in the northeast of South Africa. It borders Mozambique in the east, Zimbabwe in the north and the Crocodile River in the south.
 The park has an area of 19,500 km² and is divided into 14 different ecozones, each supporting a different animal life.
 It is one of South Africa's main attractions and is regarded as the flagship of the South African National Parks (SANParks).
 Like all South African national parks, the park charges a daily conservation fee and entrance fee.
 It can also be worth buying a Wild Card, which gives access either to selected parks in South Africa or to all South African national parks.
 Hong Kong Island is the namesake of the territory of Hong Kong and is the focus of many tourists.
 The buildings that make up the Hong Kong skyline were compared with a shimmering bar chart, which is visible through the presence of the waters of Victoria Harbour.x
 For the best views of Hong Kong, you should leave the island and head to the opposite shore of Kowloon.
 Most of Hong Kong Island's urbanization is densely packed on reclaimed land along the north coast.
 This is the place the British colonists made their own. If you are looking for traces of the area's colonial past, this is a good starting point.
 The Sundarbans are the largest mangrove forest in the world and extend over 80 km from the Bangladeshi and Indian hinterland to the coast.
 The Sundarbans have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The part of the forest that lies within the Indian state is called Sundarbans National Park.
 The forests are not only mangrove swamps, however – they also include some of the last remaining stands of the mighty jungle that once covered the Ganges plain.
 The Sundarbans extend over an area of 3,850 km², of which a third is covered by water and marshes.
 The Sundarbans have been a protected area since 1966, and it is estimated that there are now 400 Bengal tigers and about 30,000 spotted deer.
 Buses run all day from the district-wide bus station (on the other side of the river), with most buses, especially those heading east and Jakar/Bumthang, leaving between 06:30 and 07:30.
 As the buses between the districts are often full, it is recommended to buy a ticket a few days in advance.
 Most districts are served by small Japanese coaster buses, which are comfortable and stable.x
 Shared taxis offer a quick and comfortable way to get to nearby places like Paro (Nu 150) and Punakha (Nu 200).
 The Oyapock River Bridge is a suspension bridge. It crosses the Oyapock River and connects the cities of Oiapoque in Brazil and Saint-Georges de l'Oyapock in French Guiana.
 Its two towers are 83 meters high, its length is 378 meters and it has two lanes with a width of 3.50 meters.
 The clearance under the bridge is 15 meters. The construction work was completed in August 2011, but the opening to traffic was not until March 2017.
 The bridge is expected to be fully operational in September 2017, when the Brazilian customs control points are expected to be completed.
 The Guaraní were the most important indigenous group inhabiting present-day eastern Paraguay. They lived as semi-nomadic hunter-gatherers who also practiced subsistence agriculture.
 The Chaco region was also home to other groups of indigenous tribes, such as the Guaycurú and the Payaguá, who survived by hunting, gathering and fishing.x
 Paraguay, formerly known as the Great Province of the West Indies, was created in the 16th century as a result of the encounter between the Spanish conquerors and the indigenous groups.
 The Spaniards began the colonization period, which lasted three centuries.
 Since the founding of Asunción in 1537, Paraguay has managed to preserve much of its indigenous character and identity.
