 Fruit bread is widespread, with apples being baked into bread year-round and cherries and plums being used in the summer.
 Many German baked goods also contain almonds, hazelnuts or other nuts. Popular cakes often go particularly well with a cup of strong coffee.
 If you want to make small but rich pastries, try what is called Berliner, Pfannkuchen or Krapfen depending on the region.
 A curry is a dish that is based on spices and herbs, along with either meat or vegetables.
 A curry can be either "dry" or "wet" depending on the amount of liquid used.
 In the interior of northern India and Pakistan, yogurt is commonly used in curries; in southern India and some other coastal regions of the subcontinent, coconut milk is commonly used.
 With a selection of 17,000 islands, Indonesian food is an umbrella term that encompasses a wide variety of regional cuisines found throughout the country.
 However, when used without further attributes, the term generally refers to the food that originated from the central and eastern parts of the main island of Java.
 The Javanese cuisine, which is now widespread throughout the island group, offers a variety of simply seasoned dishes. The Javanese prefer peanuts, chili, sugar (especially Javanese coconut sugar) and a number of aromatic spices as flavor carriers.
 Martingales are aids for the feet of riders, which hang down on both sides of the saddle.
 They give the rider more stability, but there are safety concerns because the rider's feet may get caught in them.
 If a rider falls off a horse and gets his foot caught in the stirrup, he can be dragged along if the horse runs away. To minimize this risk, a number of safety precautions can be taken.
 First of all, most riders wear riding boots with a heel and a smooth, rather narrow sole.
 Additionally, some saddles, particularly English saddles, have safety stirrups that allow a stirrup leather to fall from the saddle as soon as it is pulled backwards by a falling rider.
 The Cochamó Valley – Chile’s premier climbing destination, known as the Yosemite of South America, with a plethora of big granite walls and cliffs.
 The peaks offer a breathtaking view. Climbers from all over the world are always discovering new routes along the walls, which offer endless possibilities.
 Downhill sports such as skiing and snowboarding are popular sports in which one attaches skis or a snowboard to one's feet and rides down a snow-covered slope.
 Skiing is a popular form of recreation with many enthusiasts, sometimes known as "ski bums", who plan their entire vacation around skiing at a particular resort.
 The idea of skiing is very old – cave paintings with depictions of skiers date back to 5000 BC!
 The origins of skiing as a sport go back at least to the 17th century, and the first recreational ski club in Australia was opened by Norwegians in 1861.
 Ski touring with a backpack: This activity is also called ski touring or ski touring.
 It resembles alpine touring skiing or mountaineering, but does not necessarily include these, as the latter is done in steep terrain and requires much firmer skis and boots.
 Consider the ski route as a comparable hiking route.
 In good conditions you are able to cover somewhat greater distances than when hiking – only very rarely will you reach the speed of cross-country skiing on well-maintained trails without a heavy backpack.
 Europe is a relatively small continent, but has numerous independent countries. Normally, one would have to apply for visas several times and go through several passport controls if one wanted to travel through several countries.
 In this respect, however, the Schengen area works a little like a country.
 As long as you stay in this zone, you can usually cross the border without having to go through passport control again.
 Accordingly, you do not need to apply for a visa for each of the Schengen member states individually, which saves time, money and bureaucracy.
 There is no universally accepted definition of what constitutes an antique. Some tax authorities define antiques as objects over 100 years old.
 The definition has geographical variations, where the age of consent may be lower in places such as North America than in Europe.
 Handmade products could be called "antique", although they are younger than similar products from mass production.
 Reindeer herding is an important source of livelihood for the Sámi, and the culture surrounding the trade is also important for many who work in other professions.
 Even in the past, not all Sámi have raised reindeer on a large scale, but have lived from fishing, hunting and similar. Reindeer were mainly used as draft animals.
 Today, many Sámi work in modern professions. Tourism is an important source of income in Sápmi, the Sámi region.
 "Even if the term 'gypsy' is used mainly by non-Roma, it is often perceived as offensive because it is associated with negative stereotypes and inaccurate perceptions of Roma."
 If a travel advisory is issued for the country you are visiting, your travel insurance or travel cancellation insurance may be affected.
 You can also consult the advice of other governments than your own. Their advice is, however, tailored to their own citizens.
 For example, American citizens in the Middle East may be confronted with different situations than Europeans or Arabs.
 Consultations are only a brief summary of the political situation in a country.
 The views presented are often superficial, general and too simplified in comparison to the more detailed information that can be found elsewhere.
 A storm is the collective term for any dangerous weather phenomenon with the potential to cause damage, severe social disruption or loss of life.
 Weather can occur anywhere in the world and there are different types of weather that depend on the geography, topography and atmospheric conditions.
 Strong winds, hail, excessive rainfall and wildfires are forms and effects of weather, as well as thunderstorms, tornadoes, flash floods and cyclones.
 Regional and seasonal weather phenomena include blizzards, snowstorms, ice storms and dust storms.
 Travellers are urged to pay attention to any type of weather that affects their area, as this can affect all travel plans.
 Anyone who plans to travel to a country that is considered a war zone should take a professional training course.
 A search on the Internet for "Course on hostile environments" will probably show the address of a local company.
 A course usually covers all the issues discussed here in much more detail, usually in combination with practical experience.
 A course is usually between 2 and 5 days long and includes role-playing, a lot of first aid and sometimes weapons training.
 There are numerous books and journals on survival in the wilderness, but few publications on war zones.
 Travellers planning to undergo gender reassignment surgery abroad should ensure that they have valid travel documents for their return journey.
 The willingness of governments to issue passports with an unspecified gender (X) or documents that have been updated to reflect the desired name and gender varies.
 The willingness of foreign governments to recognize these documents is also very different.
 Security checks at airports have also become much more intrusive since September 11, 2001.
 Transgender people before their operation should not expect their privacy and dignity to be intact when passing through the scanners.
 Rip currents are the returning flow of waves breaking on the beach, often at reefs or the like.
 Due to the underwater topography, the backflow is concentrated in a few deeper areas and a fast current can form there, even to deep water.
 Most deaths occur due to exhaustion while trying to swim back against the current, which can prove impossible.
 When you get out of the current, swimming back is not more difficult than normal.
 Try to get somewhere where you won't be caught again. Alternatively, depending on your skills and whether you've been spotted, you might want to wait for rescue.
 The return shock comes earlier than the culture shock (the honeymoon phase is not so pronounced), lasts longer and can be more serious.
 For those who have found it easy to adapt to the new culture, it is sometimes difficult to adapt to their own culture again.
 When you come back from a stay abroad, you have adapted to a different culture and dropped some of your home culture's behaviours.
 When you first traveled abroad, people were probably patient and understanding because they knew that travelers need to adjust to a new place.
 One might not expect that even returning travelers need patience and understanding.
 The sound and light show at the pyramids is one of the most interesting attractions for children in the area.
 You can see the pyramids in the dark and while it is quiet before the show begins.
 Normally, you can hear the sounds of tourists and vendors all the time. The history of the sounds and lights is just like a storybook.
 The Sphinx is used as a backdrop and narrator for a long story.
 The scenes are depicted on the pyramids, with the various pyramids being lit up.
 The South Shetland Islands, discovered in 1819, are claimed by several countries and have the most stations, with sixteen active in 2020.
 The archipelago lies 120 km north of the mainland. The largest is King George Island with the settlement of Villa Las Estrellas.
 Other islands are Livingston Island and Deception, where the flooded caldera of an active volcano provides a spectacular natural harbor.
 Ellsworthland is the region south of the peninsula, bounded by the Bellingshausen Sea.
 The mountains of the peninsula here merge into the plateau and then rise again to form the 360 km long chain of the Ellsworth Mountains, which is divided by the Minnesota Glacier.
 The northern part or the Sentinel Range has the highest mountains of Antarctica, the Vinson Massif, whose highest peak is Mount Vinson at 4,892 m (16,050 ft).
 In remote areas without cell phone coverage, a satellite phone may be the only option.
 A satellite phone is generally not a substitute for a mobile phone, as you have to be outside and in clear view of a satellite to make a call.
 The service is often used by ships, including pleasure craft, as well as expeditions requiring data and voice communications.
 Your local telephone service provider should be able to provide further information about the connection to this service.
 An increasingly popular option for people planning to take a year out is to study or take a course abroad.
 This is very popular with school graduates, as it allows them to take a year off before university without affecting their studies.
 In many cases, participation in an overseas gap year program can actually improve your chances of getting into a college or university in your home country.
 As a rule, a tuition fee is charged for enrolling in these educational programs.
 Finland is a great destination for boating. The “Land of a thousand lakes” also has thousands of islands – in the lakes and in the coastal archipelagos.
 For the archipelago and lakes you do not necessarily need a yacht.
 Even though the coastal island groups and the largest lakes are actually large enough for any yacht, smaller boats or even kayaks offer a different experience.
 Boating is the national pastime in Finland, with one in six or seven people owning a boat.
 This is comparable to Norway, Sweden and New Zealand, but otherwise quite unique (in the Netherlands, for example, the ratio is one to forty.)
 Most pure Baltic cruises include a longer stay in St. Petersburg in Russia.
 This means that you can visit the historic city for a few whole days, while returning in the evening and spending the night on the ship.
 If you only go on shore excursions, you do not need a separate visa (as of 2009).
 Some cruises offer Berlin in Germany as a destination in their brochures. As you can see on the map above, Berlin is far from the sea and a visit to the city is not included in the price of the cruise.
 Flying can be a daunting experience for people of any age and from any walk of life, especially if they have never flown before or have a traumatic experience.
 There is no need to be ashamed of this: it is nothing more than the personal fears and antipathies that many people have.
 Learning more about how airplanes work and what happens during a flight can help some people overcome the fear that comes with the unknown or with the feeling of not having any control.
 Courier companies are well paid for the fast delivery of things. Often the time is a very important factor in business documents, trade goods or spare parts for urgent repairs.
 On some routes the larger firms use their own aircraft, but on other routes and with smaller firms difficulties arose.
 When they shipped things via air freight, the unloading and customs clearance on some routes could take several days.
 The only way to get it through faster was to send it as unaccompanied baggage. The airline regulations do not allow baggage to be sent without a passenger, and that's where you come in.
 The obvious method of flying first or business class is to fork out a thick wad of cash for the privilege (or, even better, get your company to pay for it).
 This is not cheap: As a rough rule of thumb, you can expect to pay up to four times the normal economy fare for business class and eleven times the normal economy fare for first class!
 In general, it is pointless to look for discounts for business or first class seats on direct flights from A to B.
 Airlines know very well that there is a certain core group of flyers who are willing to pay a lot of money for the privilege of getting to their destination quickly and comfortably, and they charge accordingly.
 The capital of Moldova is Chisinau. The local language is Romanian, but many people also speak Russian.
 Moldova is a multiethnic republic that has suffered from ethnic conflicts.
 This conflict led to the founding of the self-proclaimed Republic of Transnistria in eastern Moldova in 1994, which has its own government and currency, but is not recognized by any UN member state.
 Despite the failure of the political negotiations, the economic relations between these two parts of the Republic of Moldova could be restored.
 The main religion in Moldova is Christian Orthodox.
 Izmir is the third largest city in Turkey with a population of about 3.7 million, the second largest port after Istanbul and a very good transport hub.
 The once ancient city of Smyrna is now a modern, progressive and busy business center, located on a huge bay and surrounded by mountains.
 The wide boulevards, glass-fronted buildings and modern shopping malls are punctuated by classic red-tiled roofs, the 18th-century market and old mosques and churches, although the city exudes a Mediterranean European atmosphere rather than the traditional Turkish one.
 The village of Haldarsvík offers views of the nearby island of Eysturoy and has an unusual octagonal church.
 On the cemetery there are some interesting marble sculptures of pigeons on some graves.
 It is worth taking a half-hour stroll through the fascinating village.
 To the north and in the immediate vicinity is the romantic and fascinating city of Sintra, which became known to foreigners after Lord Byron described its splendour in vivid colours.
 The Scotturb bus 403 runs regularly to Cabo da Roca and Sintra.
 Also visit in the north the great Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima (pilgrimage site) – a place that is world famous for its Marian apparitions.
 Please remember that you are visiting a mass grave and a place that has almost incalculable significance for a large part of the world population.
 There are still many men and women who survived their time here, and many more with relatives who were murdered or worked to death there, Jews and non-Jews alike.
 Please treat this place with the dignity, awe and respect it deserves. Do not make jokes about the Holocaust or the Nazis.
 Do not deface the site by painting or scratching graffiti.
 The official languages of Barcelona are Catalan and Spanish. About half of the inhabitants speak Catalan, the majority understand it, and almost everyone can speak Spanish.
 Most signs are only in Catalan, as it is the official language.
 Nevertheless, Spanish is also widely spoken in public transport and other facilities.
 Normal announcements are made in the Metro exclusively in Catalan, but unforeseen disruptions are reported by an automated system in a variety of languages, including Spanish, English, French, Arabic and Japanese.
 Parisians are said to be self-centered, rude and arrogant.
 Even if this is often only an inaccurate cliché, one finds oneself in Paris best if one shows one's best side and behaves like someone who is "bien élevé" (well-bred). This will make it much easier to get along.
 The brusque exterior of the Parisian quickly disappears when you follow basic manners.
 The Plitvice Lakes National Park is heavily forested, with mainly beech, spruce and fir trees, and offers a mixture of alpine and Mediterranean vegetation.
 It has a remarkable diversity of plant communities due to its numerous microclimates, different soils and varying altitudes.
 The area is also home to an extremely large variety of animal and bird species.
 There are rare fauna such as European brown bears, wolves, eagles, owls, lynxes, wild cats and capercaillie as well as many generally more common species.
 When visiting the monasteries, women must wear skirts that reach to the knees and cover their shoulders.
 In most monasteries there are indeed wrap dresses for women who come unprepared, but if you bring your own, especially one in bright colors, the monk or nun at the entrance will give you a smile.
 Similarly, men must wear trousers that reach over the knee.
 These can also be borrowed from the stock at the entrance, but the clothes are not washed after each user, so you may not feel comfortable in these dresses. For all men there is a standard size!
 The cuisine of Majorca is based, as in similar Mediterranean areas, on bread, vegetables and meat (especially pork) and always uses olive oil.
 A simple popular evening meal, especially in summer, is Pa amb Oli: Bread with olive oil, tomato and any other ingredients available such as cheese, tuna etc.
 "All nouns start with a capital letter next to the word Sie for 'you', even in the middle of a sentence."
 This is an important way to distinguish between some verbs and objects.
 It makes reading easier, but writing is somewhat difficult because you have to determine whether a verb or adjective is used as the main word.
 Italian pronunciation is relatively simple, as most words are pronounced exactly as they are written.
 The most important letters to watch out for are c and g, as their pronunciation varies depending on the following vowel.
 "Also, be careful to pronounce r and rr differently: caro means "love", while carro means "chariot.""
 Persian has a relatively simple and mostly regular grammar.
 Therefore, reading this introductory grammar would help you to learn a lot about Persian grammar and to understand sentences better.
 If you speak a romance language, it is of course easier to learn Portuguese.
 People who speak some Spanish might be tempted to think that Portuguese is so similar that it doesn't need to be learned.
 Pre-modern observatories are nowadays usually no longer in operation and serve as museums or educational sites.
 Since light pollution was not as much of a problem during their heyday as it is today, they are usually located in cities or on university campuses, which are easier to access than those built more recently.
 Most modern research telescopes are huge facilities in remote areas with favorable atmospheric conditions.
 The viewing of cherry blossoms, known as Hanami, has been a part of Japanese culture since the 8th century.
 The concept originated in China, where plum blossoms were the flower of choice.
 In Japan, the first cherry blossom festivals were held by the emperor for himself and other members of the imperial court.
 "Plants look best in their natural environment, so resist the temptation to remove just one."
 If you visit a formally laid out garden and take "samples", you will also be thrown out without discussion.
 Singapore is generally a very safe place to be, and you can find almost anything you need after you arrive.
 Since you are in the extreme tropics and only a few degrees north of the equator, you have to expect both heat (always) and strong sun (when the sky is clear, less often).
 There are also a few buses that go north to Hebron, the traditional burial site of the biblical patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, Jacob and their wives.
 Make sure that the bus you take goes to Hebron and not just to the nearby Jewish settlement of Kiryat Arba.
